Data Cleaning¶

All the different data sources have slight variations when it comes to team names - which will prove challenging when trying to group things by specific teams!

For our analysis, we are going to anchor on the trades table as our 'source of truth' for team names

In [3]:
# eliminate the * character from team names, and strip white spaces captured when web scraping
trades.To = trades.To.str.strip()
trades.From = trades.From.str.strip()

results.Team = results.Team.str.replace(' \*', '').str.strip()
results.Team = results.Team.str.replace('Borussia', 'Bor.')
stadiums.Team = stadiums.Team.str.replace('Borussia', 'Bor.')
stadiums.Team = stadiums.Team.str.replace('1. ', '')

# create a function to replace keys/values given a provided map 

def map_items(league_map):
    for k,v in league_map.items():
        results.Team[results.Team == k] = v
        trades.To[trades.To == k] = v
        trades.From[trades.From == k] = v
        stadiums.Team[stadiums.Team == k] = v
    print('Complete')

Now that we have a merged dataset, let's clean up the 'Price' column so we can perform some calculations on those values

In [13]:
def price_convert(x):

    # identify all the values to replace
    y = str(x).replace('million', '+1_000_000')\
        .replace('miillion', '+1_000_000')\
        .replace(',', '')\
        .replace('€', '')\
        .replace('\*', '')\
        .replace('(50%)', '')\
        .replace('(', '')\
        .replace(')','')\
        .strip()\
        .split('+')
    
# if there are two values returned from the split (because we're splitting on the '+' we added)
# try to multiply the two together (turning 1million to 1*1_000_000) otherwise 
# try to return the float value of the string, or return the initial value if it cant be done
    if len(y) > 1:
        return(int(np.multiply(float(y[0]),float(y[1]))))
    else:
        try:
            return(float(y[0]))
        except:
            return(y[0])
In [14]:
# apply our price function to every value in the price column
data.Price = data.Price.apply(lambda x: price_convert(x))

Trades Dates and Transfer Windows¶

Finally - let's fix the dates so that we know which trades took place in which seasons.

This is made slightly difficult because different leagues have 'mid-season' trades, where a transfer executed in January 2018 actually effects the 2017/2018 season, whereas a trade executed in June 2018 effects the 2018/2019 season.

Here is a table showing when transfer windows are open/closed:

League Summer Open Summer Close Winter Open Winter Close
England May August January January
Italy July September January January
Germany July September January February
Spain July September January February

If we want to capture the correct season, anything before March should be assigned to the 'previous season' whereas anything after March should be assigned to that years season

In [15]:
# combine the date and year variables into a new datetime column
data['transfer_season'] = data.Date.str.cat(data.Year.map(str), sep = ' ')
data['transfer_season'] = pd.to_datetime(data['transfer_season'])

# replace the year column where our transfer window rules are/arent met
data['transfer_season'] = np.where(data.transfer_season.dt.month < 3, 
                                   data.transfer_season.dt.year - 1, 
                                   data.transfer_season.dt.year)

Now that we have our cleaned data - let's define a function to map various trades across Europe

In [16]:
def draw_trades(entry, df, mode):
    
    # if we are looking at team, check the to and from columns, and assign a color column
    if mode == 'Team':
        
        if type(entry) != str:

            test = df[(df.Team_To.isin(entry) | (df.Team_From.isin(entry)))].copy().reset_index()

        else:

            test = df[(df.Team_To == entry) | (df.Team_From == (entry))].copy().reset_index()

        test['stringcolor'] = np.where(test.Team_To == entry, 'red', 'blue')
    
    # if we are looking at player, check the player column, and assign a color column    
    elif mode == 'Player':
        
        if type(entry) != str:

            test = df[(df.Player.isin(entry))].copy().reset_index()

        else:

            test = df[(df.Player == entry)].copy().reset_index()

        test['stringcolor'] = 'black'
    
    # if we don't return any values, try to return a fuzzy-matched string of what the 
    # user may have been trying to input
    if len(test) == 0:
        
        if mode == 'Player':
            value = process.extractOne(entry, df.Player)[0]
            
        elif mode == 'Team':
            value = process.extractOne(entry, df.Team_To.append(df.Team_From).unique())[0]
        
        print('No entries found. Did you mean: ' + str(value) + '?')
    
    # if everything looks good, let's build our map using plotly go
    else:
        fig = go.Figure()
    
    # add our 'from' points
        fig.add_trace(go.Scattergeo(
            locationmode = 'ISO-3',
            lon = test['Lon_From'],
            lat = test['Lat_From'],
            hoverinfo = 'text',
            mode = 'markers',
            marker = dict(
                size = 4,
                color = 'rgb(255, 0, 0)',
                line = dict(
                    width = 3,
                    color = 'rgba(68, 68, 68, 0)'
                )
            )))
    
    # add our 'to' points
        fig.add_trace(go.Scattergeo(
            locationmode = 'ISO-3',
            lon = test['Lon_To'],
            lat = test['Lat_To'],
            hoverinfo = 'text',
            mode = 'markers',
            marker = dict(
                size = 4,
                color = 'rgb(0, 0, 255)',
                line = dict(
                    width = 3,
                    color = 'rgba(68, 68, 68, 0)'
                )
            )))

        # loop through our points and draw line traces between the 'to' and 'from' points
        # where the color depends on the movement 
        for i in range(len(test)):
            fig.add_trace(
                go.Scattergeo(
                    locationmode = 'ISO-3',
                    lon = [test['Lon_From'][i], test['Lon_To'][i]],
                    lat = [test['Lat_From'][i], test['Lat_To'][i]],
                    mode = 'lines',
                    line = dict(width = 1,color = test['stringcolor'][i]),
                    hoverinfo = 'text',
                    text = ['(From) ' + test['Team_From'][i] + ': ' + test['Player'][i] + ' (' + str(test['Year'][i]) + ')', 
                            '(To) ' + test['Team_To'][i] + ': ' + test['Player'][i] + ' (' + str(test['transfer_season'][i]) + ')']
                )
            )


        # update our title and figure details    
        fig.update_layout(
            title_text = 'Trades Across Four Major European Soccer Leagues<br \>' + 'For: ' + entry,
            showlegend = False,
            geo = go.layout.Geo(
                scope = 'europe',
                projection_type = 'azimuthal equal area',
                showland = True,
                landcolor = 'rgb(243, 243, 243)',
                countrycolor = 'rgb(204, 204, 204)',
            ),
        )
        
        # if our mode is 'Team', add a legend to specify 'to' and 'from' trace colors
        if mode == 'Team':
            fig.update_layout(
                showlegend=False,
                annotations=[
                    go.layout.Annotation(
                        x=0,
                        y=1,
                        showarrow = False,
                        text="TO " + entry, 
                        font=dict(
                            color="red")
                    )
                , go.layout.Annotation(
                        x=0,
                        y=0.9,
                        showarrow = False,
                        text="FROM " + entry, 
                        font=dict(
                            color="blue")
                )]
            )

        fig.show()
        
        # return a dataframe containing all of the plotted information
        a = pd.DataFrame(test[['Date', 'Year', 'Player', 'Position', 'Price', 'From', 'To', 'transfer_season']])
        
        if mode == 'Player':
            return a.iloc[::-1]
        else:
            print('TOTAL TRANSFERS: ' + str(a['To'].count()))
            print('TRANSFERS TO: ' + str(a[a.To == entry]['To'].count()))
            print('TRANSFERS FROM: ' + str(a[a.From == entry]['From'].count()))
            print()
            print('TRANSFERS:')
            return a.sort_values('transfer_season', ascending = False)

In [24]:
# define our function to determine the type of trade
def trade_value(x):
    if (isinstance(x, int) | isinstance(x, float)):
        return 'Monetary'
    elif x == 'Loan':
        return 'Loan'
    elif x == 'Free':
        return 'Free'
    else:
        return 'Other'

# make our function to plot results by team
def plot_results(team, df, metric):

    fig = make_subplots(specs=[[{"secondary_y": True}]])
    
    data = df[df.Team == team]
    
    if data.shape[0] != 0:
    
        # Add traces
        fig.add_trace(
            go.Bar(x=data.Year, y=data[metric], name = metric),
            secondary_y=False,
        )

        fig.add_trace(
            go.Scatter(x=data.Year, y=data['Position'], name= 'Position'),
            secondary_y=True,
        )

        # Add figure title
        fig.update_layout(
            title_text= team + ' Performance over Time'
        )

        # Set x-axis title
        fig.update_xaxes(title_text="Year")

        # Set y-axes titles
        fig.update_yaxes(title_text="<b>primary: </b> " + metric, secondary_y=False)
        fig.update_yaxes(title_text="<b>secondary: </b> Position", secondary_y=True, autorange = 'reversed')

        fig.show()
    else:
        print('No results found. Did you mean: ' +  process.extractOne(team, results.Team.unique())[0])

# let's check out net trades for each position
def check_impact(metric):
    metrics = ['GF', 'GA', 'W', 'D', 'L', 'GD', 'PTS']
    
    if metric not in ['GF', 'GA', 'W', 'D', 'L', 'GD', 'PTS']:
        print('Metric not found. Please choose one of the following:')
        return metrics
    else:
        
        colors = ['red', 'green', 'blue', 'orange']
        plt.figure(figsize = (14,12))

        for i in range(4):
            plt.subplot(2,2,i+1)
            pos = total_position.pos.unique()[i]
            test = total_position[total_position.pos == pos]
            cor = round(np.corrcoef(test.Net, test[metric])[0][1],4)
            ax = sns.stripplot('Net', metric, data = test, color = colors[i])
            plt.xlabel('Net Trades by Position')
            plt.ylabel(metric)
            plt.title('Trades for  ' + pos.upper() + 'S (corr: ' + str(cor) + ')')
